text:
Consider the ruby on rails function in the User model:
```
def messages(result_limit: nil)
    hidden_subtypes = []
    Message::APP_HIDDEN_SUBTYPES.each { |subtype| hidden_subtypes << Message.sub_types[subtype] }
    messages_as_sender = Message.where(sender_id: self.id)
      .where('sub_type is NULL or sub_type NOT IN (?)', hidden_subtypes)
      .order(id: :DESC)
    messages_as_sender = messages_as_sender.limit(result_limit) if result_limit.present?

    messages_as_receiver = Message.where(receiver_id: self.id)
      .where('sub_type is NULL or sub_type NOT IN (?)', hidden_subtypes)
      .order(id: :DESC)
    messages_as_receiver = messages_as_receiver.limit(result_limit) if result_limit.present?

    return messages_as_sender.or(messages_as_receiver)
  end
```

The problem with this function is that we have indexes (receiver_id,id) and (sender_id,id) on Message model but postgres still ends up performing sort after performing BitmapOr. We would need to perform two separate queries but still return a scope to the caller. This can be done through the use of UNION ALL. Rewrite the messages function to address this performance issue.

The destination account is considered the full owner of all product licenses and will be responsible for abiding by VMware contractual policies.

Could you help me spot grammar errors in this text?          ## Building Guidelines ~~(disqualified ver.)~~
...well, this documentation should be named "Environment Setup Guidelines"... 'cause this library doesn't require any *building*.
Yes, this is a pure-header library, but OpenGL just doesn't wan't us to get away with it... as it requires compile-time and runtime dependencies introduced as executables to the project.

### The start
It's actually quite easy to just include this library, as these headers are enough for us to get work done:
`include_directories(...../qgt)`

### And then...
The following dependencies are required:
`glfw-x11` (or `glfw-wayland`) `freetype2 glm mesa`

To include them in your project:
```
find_package(OpenGL REQUIRED)
find_package(glfw3 REQUIRED)
find_package(Freetype REQUIRED)

target_link_libraries(<project> Freetype::Freetype GL glfw)
```

### Something more annoying
Since GLFW's cross-platform is made possible by GLEW/GLAD/..., we would also need a compile-time dependency.
Here we'll be using [GLAD](https://glad.dav1d.de/).
Head over to that website and generate a customized GLAD loader: select gl version > 3.3 under the API section, set `Profile` to `Core` and check `Generate a loader` before clicking on `Generate`.

...with that you'll get an archive with a .c file... Yup, that's right:
```
add_executable(<project> main.cpp.... glad.c)
include_directories(.../KHR .../glad)
```
Just include it in your project and voila! Everything should be up and running now. If you fail to

Rewrite the following ruby on rails function in the User model:
```
def messages(result_limit: nil)
    hidden_subtypes = []
    Message::APP_HIDDEN_SUBTYPES.each { |subtype| hidden_subtypes << Message.sub_types[subtype] }
    messages_as_sender = Message.where(sender_id: self.id)
      .where('sub_type is NULL or sub_type NOT IN (?)', hidden_subtypes)
      .order(id: :DESC)
    messages_as_sender = messages_as_sender.limit(result_limit) if result_limit.present?

    messages_as_receiver = Message.where(receiver_id: self.id)
      .where('sub_type is NULL or sub_type NOT IN (?)', hidden_subtypes)
      .order(id: :DESC)
    messages_as_receiver = messages_as_receiver.limit(result_limit) if result_limit.present?

    return messages_as_sender.or(messages_as_receiver)
  end
```

The problem with this function is that we have indexes (receiver_id,id) and (sender_id,id) on Message model but postgres still ends up performing sort after performing BitmapOr. We would need to perform two separate queries but still return a scope to the caller.

Zenarate AI Coach is comprised of the following modules:
1.	Speech to Text
The Speech to Text model is provided by Microsoft Azure Cognitive Services [1]. The Speech to Text model is used in a pre-trained state, and its parameters are not changed. This model was trained using Microsoft-owned data and is deployed in the cloud.
2.	Intent Mapping Engine
Agents' utterances  are converted to text and then fed to the Intent Mapping Engine, which maps them to intents . Microsoft's LUIS (Language Understanding Service) is utilized this engine to map the utterances into intents [2].
Language Understanding (LUIS) is a cloud-based, conversational AI service that employs custom machine-learning intelligence to estimate the overall meaning of a user's natural language, conversational text.
As initial seedings for the models, TD's required intents and a minimum of five utterances per intent are fed to the LUIS.
3.	 Model Story Creation
Stories  are customized by TD so that they incorporate the best practices. In each story, Zenarate plays the role of the customer. Each step/row in the call flow indicates an intent. After determining the intent of the agent's utterance using LUIS, the agent will be provided a suitable reply from AI Coach of Zenarate.

def find_global_maxima(points: Cloud) -> Union[Point, None]:
    """
    Returns the point in a point cloud with the highest z-value.

    Args:
        points (NDArray): array of shape (n, 3) representing a point cloud

    Returns:
        NDArray: array of shape (3,) representing
        the point with the highest z-value
    """
    if len(points) == 0:
        return None

    max_index = np.argmax(points[:, 2])
    return points[max_index]

text:
Consider the ruby on rails function in the User model:
```
def messages(result_limit: nil)
    hidden_subtypes = []
    Message::APP_HIDDEN_SUBTYPES.each { |subtype| hidden_subtypes << Message.sub_types[subtype] }
    messages_as_sender = Message.where(sender_id: self.id)
      .where('sub_type is NULL or sub_type NOT IN (?)', hidden_subtypes)
      .order(id: :DESC)
    messages_as_sender = messages_as_sender.limit(result_limit) if result_limit.present?

    messages_as_receiver = Message.where(receiver_id: self.id)
      .where('sub_type is NULL or sub_type NOT IN (?)', hidden_subtypes)
      .order(id: :DESC)
    messages_as_receiver = messages_as_receiver.limit(result_limit) if result_limit.present?

    return messages_as_sender.or(messages_as_receiver)
  end
```

The problem with this function is that we have indexes (receiver_id,id) and (sender_id,id) on Message model but postgres still ends up performing sort after performing BitmapOr. We would need to perform two separate queries but still return a scope to the caller. This can be done through the use of UNION ALL. Rewrite the messages function to address this performance issue.

In this kata your task is to differentiate a mathematical expression given as a string in prefix notation. The result should be the derivative of the expression returned in prefix notation.

To simplify things we will use a simple list format made up of parentesis and spaces.

The expression format is (func arg1) or (op arg1 arg2) where op means operator, func means function and arg1, arg2 are aguments to the operator or function. For example (+ x 1) or (cos x)

The expressions will always have balanced parentesis and with spaces between list items.

Expression operators, functions and arguments will all be lowercase.

Expressions are single variable expressions using x as the variable.

Expressions can have nested arguments at any depth for example (+ (* 1 x) (* 2 (+ x 1)))

Examples of prefix notation in this format:

(+ x 2)        // prefix notation version of x+2

(* (+ x 3) 5)  // same as 5 * (x + 3)

(cos (+ x 1))  // same as cos(x+1)

(^ x 2)        // same as x^2 meaning x raised to power of 2
The operators and functions you are required to implement are + - * / ^ cos sin tan exp ln where ^ means raised to power of. exp is the exponential function (same as e^x) and ln is the natural logarithm (base e).

Example of input values and their derivatives:

(* 1 x) => 1

(^ x 3) => (* 3 (^ x 2))

(cos x) => (* -1 (sin x))

"On a cool summer night, dark clouds cover the almost full moon ( as tomorrow is full moon night). The freshness in the air shakes her body to life. And she becomes alive.

All her anxieties have been washed away by the rain, all chaos in the air settled. What is left is a cool breeze of peace, optimism and a particular thing she cannot name but feels in abundance.

Is it happiness or hope? Maybe it's called gratitude? Or a mixture of all these and more? She does not know.

But one thing is for sure, she feels connected. Just for a split second, she has touched the source and essence of everything. Only for a moment, she has felt the presence of the Supreme.

For the first time in a long time, she felt that she could do anything. Ironically, the confidence came from realising that she could do nothing without him.

She is powerless, incapable of drawing the next breath without his wish, and this powerlessness gives her immense joy.

Why? Because it assures her that someone is looking out for her. Everything she has ever done, everything she has ever been, is validated by him. What she is today is his will. He knows where he is taking her, and she trusts him.

She is free from all the worries, out of all the races, competitions and comparisons. There is no personality to develop, no identity to protect.
